In MSTest v4, `TestMethodAttribute.Execute` was removed and replaced with `ExecuteAsync`. You also need to propagate the new CallerInfo constructor parameters.

Here's how to fix your attribute:

```csharp
// Before (v3)
public class RetryTestMethodAttribute : TestMethodAttribute
{
    public override TestResult[] Execute(ITestMethod testMethod)
    {
        // retry logic
        return results;
    }
}

// After (v4)
public class RetryTestMethodAttribute : TestMethodAttribute
{
    public RetryTestMethodAttribute(
        [CallerFilePath] string callerFilePath = "",
        [CallerLineNumber] int callerLineNumber = -1)
        : base(callerFilePath, callerLineNumber) { }

    public override async Task<TestResult[]> ExecuteAsync(ITestMethod testMethod)
    {
        TestResult[] results = null;
        for (int i = 0; i < MaxRetries; i++)
        {
            results = await base.ExecuteAsync(testMethod);
            if (results.All(r => r.Outcome == UnitTestOutcome.Passed))
                break;
        }
        return results;
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
1. Override `ExecuteAsync` (returns `Task<TestResult[]>`) instead of `Execute`
2. Add the `[CallerFilePath]`/`[CallerLineNumber]` constructor that forwards to `base`
3. Use `async`/`await` when calling `base.ExecuteAsync`

If your retry logic is purely synchronous and doesn't call `base`, you can use `Task.FromResult(results)` instead of `async`/`await`.
